## 4. Impact Analysis

### What an attacker could do with this

Server-side misconfigurations, depending on severity, can enable:

- **Information disclosure** — exposing server version, OS, framework versions which help attackers select targeted exploits
- **Attack surface mapping** — default pages and exposed paths reveal application structure
- **Chained exploitation** — misconfiguration information is often the first step in a larger attack chain
- **Compliance violations** — exposed headers and default configs can violate PCI-DSS and ISO 27001 requirements

### Why it matters in the GCC / enterprise context

Many enterprise applications in regulated industries (banking, government, healthcare) have strict requirements around information disclosure. Even seemingly minor misconfigurations can cause compliance failures and are commonly cited in penetration test reports.

