## 7. What I Learned

This finding reinforced several important lessons about real-world security research:

- **Reconnaissance is everything.** HTTP headers, error pages, and default paths reveal far more about a target than most developers realise.
- **Misconfigurations are underrated.** Many testers focus on code-level vulnerabilities and overlook server configuration as a finding class.
- **Even "informational" findings have value.** While this finding was rated medium/informational, it demonstrates the kind of thorough methodology that separates good security assessments from checkbox exercises.
- **Documentation matters.** Writing this up — even without a bounty payout — sharpens my ability to communicate findings clearly, which is a core skill for any penetration tester or security analyst.

